##Pangolins are being sold to China all over the world | story FM

Story

Features, welcome to the story FM. Here, we tell your story with your voice. Every Monday, Wednesday and Friday, all platforms are updated simultaneously.

Click on the picture above to jump to the "story FM" applet and listen to the real person. Remember to add "my little program" , one-click to listen to the whole story Yo!

On February 7th the South China Agricultural University announced that Pangolins were a potential intermediate host for the COVID-19.

On the eve of World Pangolin Day on February 15, we have a special program to tell you the truth about pangolins.

The narrator of today's story, Xu Jiaming, is a journalist living in Guangzhou who has worked in media outlets such as Nandu weekly. In 2019, he joined the Global Environment Report Coalition, a group of more than 30 journalists from Asia and Africa, to investigate the Pangolin's illegal trade chain.

■ wildlife experts estimate that nine out of 10 pangolins are smuggled undetected. Imagestsai Yao Zheng, Taiwan reporter

-1-

Pangolins with "milk-opening" 

I'm from the north, and when I lived in the north, I never heard of anyone eating pangolins, or knew anything about them. I have been living in Guangzhou for six years now. I have heard that there are some customs of eating game here in Guangdong. Pangolin is one of them.

I think some people might still believe that eating pangolins is good, that it can cure certain diseases.

There's a word for it —— It's supplementary.

Traditional Chinese medicine believes that pangolins have the habit of digging or digging in order to fill the shape, so pangolins have to help people dredge or open the effect. For example, Pangolin in Chinese medicine inside a medicine is "milk" . If a mother does not have enough milk after giving birth, many people believe that pangolins and pig's feet can be boiled together.

This theory of traditional Chinese medicine is particularly controversial. Many experts and animal protection agencies have come out to the public and pointed out that the scales of pangolins are mainly protein, which is the same tissue as human nails and hair, and there is no magic effect.

I've heard it mentioned at the dinner table that some people enjoy eating pangolins. I think this kind of psychology is to have face, good show off, show off I eat a very expensive, very rare thing just.

-2-

Rescue experience at Guangzhou Zoo

Before the meeting in June, I did some interviews in Guangzhou. It's hard to escape from the NGO China Biodiversity Conservation and Green Development Foundation in China to do Pangolin conservation in China.

The China Green Hair Association is a very important NGO in the field of wild and animal protection. It has a strong semi-official background, so they are more daring to do it. In the field of wild conservation, Pangolin conservation is also a very important project.

At that time, I contacted them and knew they had an ambulance operation in Guangzhou. Guangzhou customs confiscated some pangolins, they are trying to rescue, to wild release. It was also their first wild experiment, and it didn't work out.

Around the end of April last year, I saw pangolins three times around Guangzhou and Qingyuan.

Because the pangolins were rescued, when I saw these pangolins, they are dying, that state is very poor. I looked at them during the day, and they weren't moving, they were basically curled up in the corner, and they looked dirty, and they were muddy, and they weren't active.

■ Pangolins shed tears before being sent back to the rescue center under the Guangdong Forestry Bureau. Photo / Zhang Siyuan, China Biodiversity Conservation and Green Development Foundation

Sophia, a green-haired pangolin worker, was dubbed the "Pangolin girl" by the media. She came to Guangzhou from Beijing alone.

Sophia cooks for the pangolin herself, buys eggs to boil, breaks the yolks, and asks volunteers in Yunnan to send her ants. We'll help her pick out the ants that have turned to ice. When you take it out of the fridge, you have to pick out the branches and the plastic inside, and then you have to pick out the ants and beat them together with the eggs into a bowl of sesame and then give them to the pangolins.

Pangolins eat mostly ants, and many eat only termites, which are harder to find. That's why it's so hard and expensive to keep. It's not easy to find ants that feed on pangolins, because a healthy pangolin can eat at least an acre of pests like termites, and it has its own value in the ecosystem.

Like humans, Pangolins give birth only once a year and are very timid. So the Pangolin is a very typical endangered wildlife, but it is also mammals, have feelings, will cry.

For me, in fact, a deeper impression is that our rescue conditions are very general. Guangzhou zoo is already a better zoo in south China, but we do not have a special place to keep pangolins, but put it in the Lizard Room. Because lizards like that kind of stale, dark environment, so the whole row of cages is also relatively smelly.

Later learned that the garden has also done some transformation work, may also deal with later

When we went the next day, we found that the Pangolin had a tick on it, and because of the tick bite, they had to exterminate it. They squirt it on the Pangolin so that the tick drops, and in the process the Pangolin shakes and sobs, which is pathetic.

-3-

China is a consumer of Pangolins

In July 2014, the Iucn Red List Iucn Species Survival Commission Pangolin Taskforce, chaired by the Zoological Society of London, upgraded Chinese Pangolin and Sunda Pangolin to "critically endangered" . All eight species are threatened with extinction. And they warn that pangolins are by far the most trafficked mammals in the world.

After some basic research, we found that the bulk of the Pangolin trafficking goes to China, which is an absolute consumer of Pangolins. Vietnam is second only to China in terms of sales, but many pangolins end up in transit to China, even in Vietnam.

■ smuggling routes across Asia and Africa, where the bulk of Pangolin demand is believed to come from China. Data: Nepal Times

-4-

First meeting with foreign journalists

After doing basic research and writing a country report, I met with all the reporters from the global environment reporting coalition in early June to discuss the following lines of inquiry.

What we feel in journalism is that this kind of cross-border collaboration between Chinese and foreign journalists is not easy. Foreign journalists have some kind of misunderstanding or prejudice about China.

They seem to think that China will be difficult to interview, some data will be difficult to get, it will be terrible. It's not that bad. China has very open court data that many countries don't.

At that meeting, it was decided that eventually there would be a global report on the pangolin smuggling trade, in which basically every journalist would investigate in his own country. But in the end, all the reporters turned their attention to me, because they knew that it was going to China, and they wanted me to explain what it was like to actually consume pangolins in China.

■110 kilograms of pangolin scales wrapped in Tin Foil seized by Hong Kong Customs, two women from Guangxi trying to smuggle them from Hong Kong to Macau. Photo / Customs and Excise Department

-5-

"eating" and "medicinal" in the Chinese market

The main question I want to answer is: How exactly does China Use Pangolins? Are the Chinese really that into food? Are Chinese drug makers that crazy? What is the actual situation in China?

So I'm going to focus on the "eating" and the "medicinal" aspects.

Just after the meeting, I went on a food survey near Guangzhou with a group of volunteers who work as wild life insurance agents.

The volunteers were very experienced middle-aged people who knew how to deal with traffickers. But even with their cooperation, we also found that even in Guangzhou, such a place like eating game, Pangolin is not so easy to eat. Because it's clearly against the law, and if you get called in, the police will actually come after you.

Of course, it also has something to do with the background of anti-corruption. Because the Pangolin is very expensive, basically is when the official and rich people in the food, eat a pangolin about 10,000 yuan. So the last two years there is still eat, but a lot less than before, the market is much smaller.

And then we're going to answer the medicinal part. How much Chinese Pangolin is used in medicine?

One of the biggest legal loopholes in China is the use of traditional Chinese medicine. Pangolins are legal in China. Our country abides by international treaties, which do not allow pangolins to be traded, cooked or sold for money. But the use of pangolins is legal, and there are about 60 or 70 kinds of Chinese medicines that use pangolins.

In China, it's easy to buy legitimate medicinal pangolin scales. In Guangzhou, Foshan, Shantou, Guangxi, Nanning and other cities, we can find pharmacies to buy legal pangolin scales. Its price is about 7 yuan to 10 yuan a gram, is a relatively expensive Chinese medicine.

In fact, before 2015, our national forestry system has a saying that China has an inventory system, and all of our legitimate pangolin approvals come from the inventory system. The annual volume is about 25 tons, this amount should be far from enough to meet the needs of the Chinese market.

Because China will often find dozens of tons of smuggling cases. The demand for smuggling is so great, but only 25 tons a year, and after 2015 the data is not public.

This is also a point that the China Green Hair Association has been calling for government information to be made public. They went out in public to write pleadings or to write application reports, but got no response. So that's a pretty big hole.

■ A pharmacy in Shantou sells scaly pangolins without legal labels for 6 Renminbi per gram, which sales staff say is good for opening milk. Photoglobal alliance for environmental reporting

So China has stocks, but we don't disclose how much we have, and there are two problems with that:

1. Will what we confiscate and seize end up on the legal market?

2. What is the quantity and prevalence of the legal market?

To answer the second question, what is the situation of Chinese pharmaceutical factories. In this regard, the China Green Hair Association has a good report, in the first two years they have a legal use of Chinese medicine in the quasi-character list of Pangolin ingredients. It shouldn't be hard to find out. Even sales, the public should be able to find out. But I ran it through a lot of databases, and I couldn't find any data on the 2019 pangolins, so I had to rely on the 2016 tables.

We checked. Most of the drugs are still in the chart. About two or three of these factories are in Guangdong, so we went to these factories.

Luckily, we met one of the purchasing directors at one of the factories. He trusted us very much and showed us the approval from Tianjin in his hand. A factory in Guangdong used the approval from Tianjin, and the dosage was 800 kg. He told me it was a small amount.

Because it is not a very large plant, such a plant about a month will use 800 kilograms, we 25 tons of volume is not able to withstand scrutiny.

One Clue we get from interviews and undercover interviews may be that there may be some obvious places in China to monitor the "medicinal" sector.

-6-

Myanmar investigation

Because the native Chinese Pangolin is so endangered that it is hard to find any pangolins and scales available in China these days are usually smuggled from Southeast Asia or Africa.

According to our investigation of African journalists, buyers from China have gone deep into African villages to buy pangolins directly.

In the course of this investigation, in addition to domestic, I also with the cooperation of local reporters, secretly visited Vietnam and Myanmar trading chain. I was most impressed by what I saw in Burma.

■ The pangolin was rescued from an online wildlife trafficker during a reporter's undercover investigation. Pangolins were later released into the jungle by the Malaysian Department of Wildlife and the National Park Peninsula. Photo / Global Environment Report Coalition

The Myanmar trip was from November 14 to December 12 last year.

Burmese people have a bad impression of the Chinese because they think of China as a country that takes away Myanmar's resources. China is a country that asks a lot of them, and although it pays, the money does not necessarily benefit everyone. Because Burma is a military government, and a lot of places are still opaque and private, ordinary people, or people I talk to, have this idea about the Chinese.

In Myanmar, I began my interviews by infiltrating the Chinese community.

That's the only Chinese lawyer I've ever met. He was discreet and he talked a lot. He revealed that eating pangolins is actually very easy in Burma, and that there is a restaurant known to their circle of Chinese.

When I got the clue, I went to the restaurant. Once there, it was a world of gray-business Chinese. The hotel felt exactly like a Beijing hotel, with everyone drunk and smelling of Baijiu. All kinds of southern and northern dialects, everyone is bragging, talking nonsense, talking about women, talking about how much money they have made, complaining... They are very open, very loud, like any restaurant in China.

■ Xu Jiaming sees pangolins at a restaurant in Yangon

Then we ordered some normal food, talked to the boss, said we wanted to eat Pangolin, want to entertain people. The boss on the spot agreed that no reservations, they have done this for more than 10 years, very confident.

This is not what we see in China and Vietnam. In China, the boss is very cautious, you need three or four times to go to dinner, he may give you a little information, may believe you. In Vietnam, too, you have to book a week in advance.

After dinner and the check, I told my boss I wanted to take a look before I felt relieved. He casually called a cook to take me to the back kitchen and pulled out an Armadillo. I hadn't seen a live Pangolin in six months, and this time it looked so pathetic, curled up on the ground, that I took a few pictures.

Opposite the restaurant is a specialty shop, which also sells scales and Pangolin powder. The price is not low, about a kilogram may be more than 3,000 yuan. And the boss wouldn't let us buy nail Polish, saying, "you can't take it with you. It's dangerous. ". So I went along with it and said, "can you do it for me? " , but the boss said he couldn't.

Pangolins are easy to eat in Rangoon, easy to buy, and a little hard to transport.

■ In June 2019, Philippine authorities seized 10 pangolins in Tagaytay City and arrested three men. Photograph Department of Environment and Natural Resources, Philippines

-7-

Visit to Tachileik

Then I went to Tachileik, on the eastern border of Burma. Tachileik is notorious as the heart of Golden Triangle. Drug Lord Khun Sa has lived in this city since the 1990s, making it his home base. Now there are a lot of Chinese there, too, because there are gold mines nearby.

When I got here, I saw the Pangolin again.

Because there are Chinese people, there will be Chinese people to eat it will be sold. It was easy for me to find out that the sellers were in the market just before 8 or 9 am in the morning. Then I went and saw a Burmese lady selling pangolins on the side of the road. Because she is tied to a monkey, very conspicuous, next to the stall may be a tiger or leopard jaw teeth, there are some birds in the cage, and some insects are also sold.

I asked in Burmese, "Pangolin, " and the Burmese lady understood. She made a phone call, and her husband brought over an Armadillo.

This pangolin impressed me very much, it is the best body, the most lively, the most robust Pangolin I have ever seen. After they threw it into the box, the Pangolin immediately climbed over the box to escape, so fast that the monkey kept by the Burmese elder sister was screaming. The original health of the Pangolin, it is so fast crawling speed!

But the Pangolin is really easy to be subdued by human, Myanmar elder sister is very experienced, grab that Pangolin's Tail, pat it, it is afraid to shrink.

■ The seller pats the Pangolin, lifts it up, and slips it back into a nylon bag

I am to ask as a buyer, the price of this pangolin about 3,000,4,000 yuan.

After the interview, I felt sick for a while. Because I saw all kinds of forms of pangolins, healthy, fragile, dead, they have to be eaten by the Chinese, I was to buy as a Chinese identity, open a restaurant is also to serve the Chinese, feel very complex. Seeing the connection between pangolins and US Chinese, I myself, as a Chinese, still feel a little uncomfortable.

-8-

Status of illegal trade

We asked two local logistics people about how to get it to China, and they probably offered two ways.

The first is the simplest. China has a "border people-to-people trade" policy in the border areas. Local people hold relevant documents and can carry some things across the border every day. Ask the local people to take care of you bit by bit through the form of "ants moving house" . It may be less but the risk is the lowest.

Another way is through the local logistics company transport. Because a container truck or a van is so big, he can blend pangolin scales into tons of stuff. The same is equivalent to the "ant move" , the large goods into pieces to China.

Each of them knew that it was illegal to smuggle pangolins, but everyone was doing it, and everyone told me with ease, "it can be done, you can rest assured. ".

■ from Móng Cái, Vietnam, just across the river from its sister city of Dongxing, in Guangxi Province, China, reporters found that underground smuggling, including pangolins, was still active. Photoglobal alliance for environmental reporting

Our editor asked a question: Since locals in Myanmar don't have the habit of consuming pangolins, they are mostly sold to the Chinese, and buying and selling pangolins in Myanmar is also illegal, so why didn't Burma rein in the Pangolin Trade?

Our Burmese reporter gave an example. A friend of hers, a photographer who specializes in anti elephant poaching, told her that in those border mountains, the Burmese police had worse guns than poachers, and that when the police saw poachers, they would run, because the poachers have better guns and more people.

I've been to Myanmar twice, and I also feel that Myanmar may or may not have the power to stop the Pangolin trade for reasons of race, economic development, etc. .

——————

There are two trends in China. One is that the legal environment for providing protection is improving, as the state is proposing to upgrade the Pangolin to a level 1 protected animal, which would then be approved for medicinal use by the State Council.

Even when I read a recent report that the Director General of the CITES had come to China, State Forestry Administration of the People's Republic of China officials told her that they would advocate the commercialization of pangolins and ban their commercial use, try not to medicate except in rare cases.

Another is that the Chinese media or ngos can do more to monitor and focus on the authorities they have power over, mainly the forestry sector and customs.

I hope the Chinese try not to eat wild food, because it is uncivilized and dangerous. I hope the younger generation of the post-90s and post-80s generation don't get into this habit, because it's not cool at all.
